    "summary": "The Neo-Babylonian Empire (626–539 BC), also called the Chaldean Empire, was the last great Mesopotamian empire — a dynasty that rose to fill the power vacuum left by Assyria's fall, briefly dominating the Near East before falling to the Persian Achaemenids. Founded by Nabopolassar, who allied with the Medes to destroy Nineveh, the empire reached its apogee under his son [[event:1905|Nebuchadnezzar II]], who conquered the Levant including Judah, destroyed Jerusalem (see [[event:1909|Destruction of Solomon Temple]]), and deported Jewish elites to Babylon (see [[event:1908|Babylonian Captivity Judah]]).\n\nBabylon under the Neo-Babylonian kings was rebuilt into the largest and most magnificent city in the ancient world: the [[event:1906|Hanging Gardens of Babylon]], the [[event:1907|Ishtar Gate Construction]], the great ziggurat Etemenanki (possibly the historical basis for the Tower of Babel), and city walls allegedly wide enough for two chariots to pass abreast. The empire invested heavily in astronomy and mathematics, developing techniques for predicting planetary motion and lunar eclipses with remarkable precision — the foundation of later Hellenistic astronomy. The last Neo-Babylonian king, Nabonidus, was absent from Babylon for years at the oasis of Tayma in Arabia in mysterious circumstances, which historians have interpreted variously as religious devotion, political exile, or mental illness. His son Belshazzar governed as regent, and both were overthrown by Cyrus the Great in 539 BC (see [[event:1913|Fall of Babylon to Persia]]).",
    "wikipedia_url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Neo-Babylonian_Empire",
